Why Do We Need Ridge & Lasso?

Imagine we trained a Linear Regression model.

It performs:

✅ Very well on training data
❌ Poorly on test data

This is called Overfitting.

Why does overfitting happen?
Too many features
Noise in data
Highly correlated features
Model learns unnecessary patterns

We need a way to make the model simpler.

This is where Regularization comes in.

What is Regularization?

Regularization is a technique that penalizes large coefficient values so the model becomes simpler and generalizes better.

Instead of only minimizing prediction error, we also penalize complexity.

Goal:

Reduce overfitting
Improve generalization
Prevent very large coefficients
Recall Linear Regression Cost Function

For Linear Regression:

Cost=MSE

The model only tries to reduce prediction error.

If coefficients become very large, Linear Regression doesn't care.

Example:

Price = 2x1 + 150x2 + 400x3

Large coefficients may indicate overfitting.

Ridge Regression (L2 Regularization)
Idea

Ridge adds a penalty equal to the square of the coefficients.

New Cost Function:

Cost=MSE+λ∑w
i
2
	​


where:

MSE → Prediction error
λ (lambda) → Regularization strength
w → Model coefficients
Ridge Intuition

Suppose the model learns:

x1 = 250
x2 = 300
x3 = -450

These huge values increase the penalty.

The optimizer reduces them:

250 → 40
300 → 60
-450 → -70

The coefficients become smaller.

Important: Ridge makes coefficients small, but rarely exactly zero.

Effect of Lambda (λ)
λ = 0

No regularization.

Same as Linear Regression.

Small λ
Slight penalty
Small coefficient reduction
Good balance
Large λ
Strong penalty
Coefficients become very small
May underfit
Advantages of Ridge
Reduces overfitting
Handles multicollinearity well
Uses all features
Stable model
Disadvantages of Ridge
Does not remove unnecessary features
Less interpretable
All variables remain in the model
Lasso Regression (L1 Regularization)
Idea

Lasso adds the absolute values of coefficients as the penalty.

New Cost Function:

Cost=MSE+λ∑∣w
i
	​

∣
Lasso Intuition

Suppose the model learns:

x1 = 100
x2 = 60
x3 = 2
x4 = 0.5

Lasso realizes that:

x3 contributes very little
x4 contributes almost nothing

Instead of just reducing them:

x3 → 0
x4 → 0

The features are removed from the model.

This is called Feature Selection.

Why Does Lasso Remove Features?

Because the absolute value penalty encourages coefficients to become exactly zero.

Example:

Before:

Price = 10x1 + 8x2 + 2x3 + 0.5x4

After Lasso:

Price = 10x1 + 8x2

Features x3 and x4 are eliminated.

Advantages of Lasso
Reduces overfitting
Performs automatic feature selection
Produces simpler models
Easy to interpret
Disadvantages of Lasso
May remove useful correlated features
Can underfit if λ is too high
Less stable with highly correlated variables
Ridge vs Lasso
Ridge	Lasso
L2 Regularization	L1 Regularization
Uses squared coefficients	Uses absolute coefficients
Shrinks coefficients	Shrinks and removes coefficients
Feature selection ❌	Feature selection ✅
Handles multicollinearity well	Can drop correlated features
Better when most features matter	Better when many features are irrelevant
Ridge Example

Features:

Age
Salary
Experience
Height

Ridge learns:

Age = 0.9
Salary = 1.2
Experience = 0.6
Height = 0.05

Every feature remains.

Lasso Example

Same data:

Age = 0.9
Salary = 1.2
Experience = 0
Height = 0

The model removes Experience and Height because they contribute very little.

When to Use Ridge?

Use Ridge when:

Most features are useful
Features are highly correlated
Need stable predictions
Don't want to remove variables

Examples:

House Price Prediction
Stock Price Prediction
Sales Forecasting
When to Use Lasso?

Use Lasso when:

Many unnecessary features exist
Need feature selection
Want a simple model
Need better interpretability

Examples:

Medical diagnosis
Gene selection
Text classification
Ridge vs Linear Regression
Linear Regression	Ridge
Can overfit	Less overfitting
Large coefficients allowed	Penalizes large coefficients
Higher variance	Lower variance
Better training accuracy	Better test accuracy
Lasso vs Linear Regression
Linear Regression	Lasso
Uses every feature	Removes unimportant features
No feature selection	Automatic feature selection
More complex	Simpler model
Common Mistakes
Choosing a very high λ can cause underfitting.
Ridge is not used for feature selection.
Lasso may remove useful correlated features.
Always standardize features before applying Ridge or Lasso because the penalty depends on coefficient magnitudes.
Interview Questions
1. Why do we use Ridge Regression?

Answer: To reduce overfitting by shrinking coefficient values using L2 regularization.

2. Why do we use Lasso Regression?

Answer: To reduce overfitting and perform automatic feature selection by making some coefficients exactly zero.

3. What is Regularization?

Answer: A technique that adds a penalty to the cost function to reduce model complexity and improve generalization.

4. Which regularization is used in Ridge?

Answer: L2 Regularization (squared coefficients).

5. Which regularization is used in Lasso?

Answer: L1 Regularization (absolute coefficients).

6. Which algorithm performs feature selection?

Answer: Lasso Regression.

7. Which algorithm handles multicollinearity better?

Answer: Ridge Regression.

8. What does λ (lambda) control?

Answer: The strength of regularization. A larger λ increases the penalty on coefficients.
